## Withering

As soon as a tea leaf is plucked, it begins to wilt. Withering is essentially the process of 
controlled wilting, which prepares the leaves for processing by reducing their moisture content. 
The process usually occurs either outside or indoors in troughs with forced air.
The withering process is complete once the tea leaves have lost around 30-50% of their moisture, 
which typically takes 8-20 hours. 

The withering process causes the membranes of the tea leaves to open, making them more supple and 
less prone to breaking in further processing steps. Withering also has chemical effects: the 
chlorophyll in the leaf begins to disintegrate, caffeine levels increase, new flavor and aroma 
compounds develop, and grassy flavors dissipate. So, the "grassier" teas, like green tea, are 
typically withered for a short amount of time, or sometimes not at all.

