## Oxidizing

Fixing is the process of slightly heating the tea leaves. This procedure is done to stop the 
oxidation of the leaves, which begins during the withering process as the cells in the leaves 
are damaged. The heat denatures the oxidative enzymes in the leaf and greatly slows the oxidation process.

A tea that has been fixed retains its green color and vegetal taste. Semi-oxidized tea leaves 
present with a slight browning, and produce a more yellow liquid with a more complex flavor. 
Fully oxidized tea leaves will be a dark brown and produce a dark red liquid. Thus, controlling the 
oxidation of the leaves controls the flavor and chemcial profile of the tea.

